{"id":14881535,"mediaExerciseId":"74c09cd6-fc9e-4d3d-898e-33d1557cfe69","exerciseName":"4","chapterName":"16","chapterTitle":"Financial Leverage and Capital Structure Policy","groupId":null,"groupTitle":null,"isPremium":true,"sectionName":"16.4","sectionTitle":"M&M Propositions I and II with Corporate Taxes","pageNumber":550,"solutions":[{"id":5991884,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"$a)$ Whenever the effect of corporation tax is taken into account as in the situation of such an unlevered firm, the firm's overall weighted average cost of capital lowers due to its substantial reliance on debt financing. \n\nAs the cost of equity of the leveraged firm, on the other hand, rises even as the firm relies increasingly on riskier financing, as a consequence, stockholders' expectations rise, resulting in a greater cost of equity.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":218,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/07/1e009cc2ff45c248e31a14e0854dc7b5/19479678fc4686e8098ef78d5bc8b53a/lateximg_large.png","width":1029},"regular":{"height":110,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/07/1e009cc2ff45c248e31a14e0854dc7b5/19479678fc4686e8098ef78d5bc8b53a/lateximg.png","width":515}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"$b)$ As only tax effects are taken into account, an all-debt capital structure with no equity is the best option, it is because the company will benefit from a tax break on the interest it pays, increasing its value and lowering its cost of capital. \n\nAs a consequence, using a hundred percent debt would be the best financial structure for the company.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":218,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/07/1e009cc2ff45c248e31a14e0854dc7b5/b1316dabbf68277ae004b14e5bc1e394/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":110,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/07/1